<voice name="V2">
<prosody rate="95%" pitch="-2st">

When most people hear NVIDIA, <break time="300ms"/> they think of graphics cards. <break time="200ms"/> Gamers. <break time="200ms"/> GPUs.

<break time="600ms"/>

But that is the old story.

<break time="500ms"/>

The new story is this. <break time="400ms"/> NVIDIA is no longer just a hardware company. <break time="300ms"/> It is a <emphasis level="strong">full-stack AI platform provider</emphasis>.

<break time="500ms"/>

From the silicon in the data center to the APIs developers call in production. <break time="300ms"/> NVIDIA now touches every layer of the AI system.

<break time="700ms"/>

If you want to understand how agentic AI gets deployed at scale, <break time="300ms"/> you need to understand this stack. <break time="300ms"/> Not as marketing. <break time="300ms"/> As <emphasis level="strong">architecture</emphasis>.

<break time="600ms"/>

This module walks you through the layers. <break time="300ms"/> From hardware to application. <break time="300ms"/> From CUDA to NIM.

<break time="1200ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: The Problem of Production AI.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us frame the problem before we introduce the solution.

<break time="500ms"/>

Building AI systems at production scale is hard. <break time="300ms"/> Not because the models are hard. <break time="300ms"/> Because the infrastructure is complex.

<break time="400ms"/>

You need GPUs. <break time="200ms"/> You need software that extracts performance from those GPUs. <break time="200ms"/> You need inference servers that handle requests at scale. <break time="200ms"/> You need integration surfaces for enterprise systems.

<break time="500ms"/>

Failure mode: fragile infrastructure. <break time="300ms"/> Every layer is a potential failure point.

<break time="500ms"/>

Historically, companies built this themselves. <break time="300ms"/> They stitched together open-source tools and custom scripts. <break time="300ms"/> It worked but was fragile. <break time="300ms"/> Every upgrade was a risk.

<break time="600ms"/>

Definition: The NVIDIA AI Platform Stack is a unified platform where each layer is designed to work with the others.

<break time="500ms"/>

Enterprise driver: reduced complexity. <break time="300ms"/> Let engineers focus on applications, not infrastructure plumbing.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: The Five Layers.

<break time="500ms"/>

The stack has five major layers.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Layer 1: Hardware.</emphasis>

<break time="400ms"/>

At the base is NVIDIA GPU hardware. <break time="300ms"/> Data center GPUs like H100 and Blackwell. <break time="200ms"/> Networking fabric like NVLink and InfiniBand. <break time="200ms"/> High-bandwidth memory for large models.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: this layer is about throughput, latency, and memory constraints.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: this layer is about capital expenditure and roadmap alignment.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Layer 2: Acceleration.</emphasis>

<break time="400ms"/>

On top of hardware sits the acceleration layer. <break time="300ms"/> This is where CUDA lives.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: CUDA is NVIDIA's parallel computing platform for GPU code execution.

<break time="400ms"/>

Raw CUDA is low-level. <break time="300ms"/> Most AI workloads use libraries built on CUDA. <break time="200ms"/> cuDNN for deep learning. <break time="200ms"/> cuBLAS for linear algebra. <break time="300ms"/> And <emphasis level="moderate">TensorRT</emphasis> for inference optimization.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: TensorRT compiles trained models into optimized execution graphs for faster inference.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: TensorRT is what makes production inference economically viable.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Layer 3: Inference Serving.</emphasis>

<break time="400ms"/>

Once you have an optimized model, you need to serve it.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: Triton Inference Server is NVIDIA's platform for running models in production.

<break time="400ms"/>

Triton handles request batching. <break time="200ms"/> Model versioning. <break time="200ms"/> Multi-model serving. <break time="200ms"/> GPU scheduling. <break time="200ms"/> Health monitoring.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: Triton supports TensorRT, PyTorch, TensorFlow, and ONNX formats.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: operational reliability.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Layer 4: Model and Runtime Surfaces.</emphasis>

<break time="400ms"/>

This is where NeMo and NIM enter the picture.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: NeMo is NVIDIA's framework for building and customizing large language models.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: NIM is NVIDIA Inference Microservices. <break time="200ms"/> Pre-packaged, optimized containers for production deployment.

<break time="400ms"/>

You pull a NIM, run it, and you have a production-ready endpoint. <break time="300ms"/> No manual optimization. <break time="200ms"/> No infrastructure configuration.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: NIMs reduce time-to-production significantly.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: NIMs are designed for agentic workloads with streaming and function calling support.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Layer 5: Application Layer.</emphasis>

<break time="400ms"/>

At the top sits the application layer. <break time="300ms"/> This is where your agentic system lives. <break time="300ms"/> You orchestrate NIMs with planning logic, tool integrations, and safety layers.

<break time="400ms"/>

NVIDIA provides blueprints and reference architectures. <break time="300ms"/> But this layer is where your differentiation happens.

<break time="400ms"/>

The stack below is platform. <break time="300ms"/> The application layer is where you build.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Why the Stack Matters for Agents.

<break time="500ms"/>

Why does this stack matter for agentic AI?

<break time="500ms"/>

Agents are latency-sensitive. <break time="200ms"/> Compute-intensive. <break time="200ms"/> Operationally complex. <break time="300ms"/> They make multiple model calls per user interaction.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: fast inference is required for responsive agent loops.

<break time="500ms"/>

TensorRT optimizes the model. <break time="200ms"/> Triton handles serving at scale. <break time="200ms"/> NIM packages everything for deployment.

<break time="500ms"/>

Compare this to calling a third-party API for every inference. <break time="300ms"/> You are subject to their latency, rate limits, and pricing.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: control. <break time="300ms"/> Run inference yourself with tooling designed for the task.

<break time="500ms"/>

For engineers: the stack reduces time-to-production. <break time="300ms"/> You focus on application logic.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: the stack reduces risk. <break time="300ms"/> You build on a supported platform with enterprise support.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Certification Alignment.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification expects you to understand the platform stack at a conceptual level.

<break time="500ms"/>

Expect questions about the role of each layer. <break time="300ms"/> What does TensorRT do? <break time="200ms"/> What problem does Triton solve? <break time="200ms"/> What is a NIM?

<break time="500ms"/>

This aligns with NVIDIA exam domains around platform components and deployment contexts.

<break time="500ms"/>

You should understand the relationship between layers. <break time="300ms"/> TensorRT optimizes. <break time="200ms"/> Triton serves. <break time="200ms"/> NIM packages both. <break time="300ms"/> That flow is testable.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification also covers on-premises versus cloud versus edge deployment. <break time="300ms"/> Understand the tradeoffs.

<break time="500ms"/>

NIM is particularly important. <break time="300ms"/> It is NVIDIA's primary interface for agentic deployment.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="98%">

Section: Key Takeaways.

<break time="600ms"/>

NVIDIA is a full-stack AI platform provider. <break time="300ms"/> From hardware to application.

<break time="500ms"/>

The five layers are hardware, acceleration, inference serving, model surfaces, and application.

<break time="500ms"/>

For agentic workloads, this stack provides low-latency, high-throughput infrastructure.

<break time="500ms"/>

NIMs are the deployment surface for agentic AI. <break time="300ms"/> Optimized containers ready for production.

<break time="500ms"/>

Know the layers. <break time="200ms"/> Know the components. <break time="200ms"/> Know why they matter.

<break time="600ms"/>

This is the platform that agentic AI runs on. <break time="400ms"/> Now you know how it works.

<break time="1000ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

